Part I: Practice Questions

Problem 1

Using the seatpos data, perform a PCR analysis with hipcenter as the response and HtShoes, Ht, Seated, Arm, Thigh, and Leg as predictors. Select an appropriate number of components and give an interpretation to those you choose. Add Age and Weight as predictors and repeat the analysis. Use both models to predict the response for predictors taking these values: \[\begin{align*} \sf{Age} &= 64.800\\ \sf{Weight} &= 263.700\\ \sf{HtShoes} &= 181.080\\ \sf{Ht} &= 178.560\\ \sf{Seated} &= 91.440\\ \sf{Arm} &= 35.640\\ \sf{Thigh} &= 40.950\\ \sf{Leg} &= 38.790 \end{align*}\]

Observe that the first component alone explains 94.53% of the variation in the response, while the first and the second explain 97.22% of the variation in the response.

Now, we run a principal components regression. We use Cross-Validation to select the optimal number of components:

set.seed(100)
seatpos.pcr1 = pcr(hipcenter~HtShoes+Ht+Seated+Arm+Thigh+Leg, data=seatpos, validation="CV") 
summary(seatpos.pcr1)

Both the plot and the min CV value indicate that the second term (i.e. one component) is sufficient.

In ridge regression, we need to find the optimal lambda. Here it is equal to 22.32. So, we use this model for prediction:

ridgebest = lm.ridge(hipcenter~., data=seatpos, lambda=22.3223223)

Part II: Homework Questions

Problem 1

In the following questions choose the correct answer. Justify your answer.

  1. The Lasso, relative to Ordinary Least Squares, is:
    1. More flexible and hence will give improved prediction accuracy when its increase in bias is less than its decrease in variance.
    2. More flexible and hence will give improved prediction accuracy when its increase in variance is less than its decrease in bias.
    3. Less flexible and hence will give improved prediction accuracy when its increase in bias is less than its decrease in variance.
    4. Less flexible and hence will give improved prediction accuracy when its increase in variance is less than its decrease in bias.


    Correct Answer: (iii) Less flexible and hence will give improved prediction accuracy when its increase in bias is less than its decrease in variance.

    We know that the OLS give the BLUE (best linear unbiased estimators. But, when compared with “biased” estimators, then they tend to have higher bias. We discussed that the LASSO estimators are biased. However, we can control the bias-variance trade-off and reduce the number of coefficients in the model (a stricter penalty will lead many coefficients to be zero) which will ultimately lead in a decrease in the variance (followed by an increase in the bias).


  2. The Ridge Regression, relative to Ordinary Least Squares, is:
    1. More flexible and hence will give improved prediction accuracy when its increase in bias is less than its decrease in variance.
    2. More flexible and hence will give improved prediction accuracy when its increase in variance is less than its decrease in bias.
    3. Less flexible and hence will give improved prediction accuracy when its increase in bias is less than its decrease in variance.
    4. Less flexible and hence will give improved prediction accuracy when its increase in variance is less than its decrease in bias.


    3. Correct Answer: (iii) Less flexible and hence will give improved prediction accuracy when its increase in bias is less than its decrease in variance. For the same reasons as for the LAsso.

In this problem, we are going to use the data set from the package. The goal is to predict the acceptance rate of a college (number of applications accepted / number of applications received) using the other variables in the data set.

library(ISLR)

Let’s plot the response against the remaining variables

  1. Split the data set in two parts: a and a data set. Choose 30% of the data at random for testing, and use the remaining for training. (Fix the seed to 425). Define the response rate as Rate = Accept/Apps. Plot this variable against every variable in the data set.

  3. Use AIC, BIC, and Adjusted $R^2$ to select a potentially smaller model, from the set of all possible predictors used in the previous question. Report which model each method chose, and the training and testing errors for their chosen model(s).

    library(leaps)
college.subsets = regsubsets(Rate ~ ., data=train, nvmax = ncol(train)-1)
college.subsets.summary = summary(college.subsets)

n = dim(train)[1]
msize = 2:17

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(msize, college.subsets.summary$adjr2, xlab="No. of Parameters", ylab = "Adjusted Rsquare") 
Aic = n*log(college.subsets.summary$rss/n) + 2*msize; 
plot(msize, Aic, xlab="No. of Parameters", ylab = "AIC"); 
Bic = n*log(college.subsets.summary$rss/n) + msize*log(n); 
plot(msize, Bic, xlab="No. of Parameters", ylab = "BIC")

    Adjusted \(R^2\)

    The optimal model according to Adjusted \(R^2\) has

    which.max(college.subsets.summary$adjr2)
    ## [1] 14

  6. Fit a PCR model on the training set, with M chosen by cross-validation. Report the test error obtained, along with the value of M selected by cross-validation.

model.pcr = pcr(Rate ~., data=train.s, validation="CV")

    # M = components that correspond to min RMSE

    #  RMSE

    ## [1] 0.8416969
    # Testing/ Training Errors
ptrain.pcr = predict(model.pcr, train.s, ncomp=16)
ptest.pcr = predict(model.pcr, test.s, ncomp=16)

mean((train.s$Rate - ptrain.pcr)^2)
    ## [1] 0.6474773
    mean((test.s$Rate - ptest.pcr)^2)
    ## [1] 0.6579451

  7. Comment on the results obtained. How accurately can we predict the acceptance rate overall? Which approach would you recommend for this data set and why?

    First of all, not that the testing errors are lower than the corresponding training errors. This is expected since our model was fitted based on the training data and the testing errors are “out-of-sample” prediction errors.

    In order to select the best approach for this data, we have to look at the prediction errors in the testing data set, if prediction is our goal. In our case, RIDGE, LASSO and PCR models tend to have a relatively high prediction error on the testing data.

    Assuming we’re interested in performing prediction, to choose the optimal approach we have to look at the RMSE values for the testing dataset (from these we get an idea on how the model performs with “unseen” data, which is the case for prediction). Even though there is no established threshold for what constitutes a “good” and a “bad” RMSE, given the fact that our dependent variable (“Rate”) takes values from 0 to 1, we can see that the RMSE (testing dataset) for the RIDGE, LASSO and PCR models are really high (all of them around 0.8). All the least-squares models have lower errors, so we should choose one of these. The lowest error is obtained using the AIC criterion while at the same time the number of predictors selected is reasonable.
